The defendant Timothy E Willey was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Theft-Movable Property >$10,000, a class G felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.20(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Amendment to Judgment of Conviction extending Probation for 2 years - from 7/30/19.  
New discharge date:  7/30/21;

09:35 AM  Court in session.  Case called.  Appearances given.  DA Intern  Bryan Charbogian appears for State under supervision of ADA Haley Johnson.  Defendant Timothy E. Willey is present.  Probation Agent Doua Xiong appears.  Agent indicates there is approximately $13,000 in restitution still owed and he has paid about $1500.00.  Last payment was from March 7, 2019.  He was supposed to be paying $100 per month but pays periodically when he can.  Deft says almost 3 years ago, his wife left him.  He is on social security disability.  His ex-wife was bringing in about $3,000 per month in income.  He has a part-time job now - approximately 10 to 20 hours of work every 2 weeks.  He plans on continuing to pay the $100 per month but it has just been hard.  Agent Xiong says he has been doing well on probation.  State is concerned on how little restitution has been paid.  Court extends probation for another 2 years and asks that he pay $100 per month if not more if he can.  Court explains that even if discharged at some point in time, the remaining restitution would be reduced to a civil judgment against the defendant.  Agent Xiong is to prepare paperwork for the extension.  9:42 am  Court in recess.
Probation review hearing on July 2, 2019 at 09:30 am.
